04904nam a22007335i 9781400844630DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122013nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008446307 a10.1515/97814008446302doi  a(DE-B1597)453866  a(OCoLC)979578976  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQB651b.Y46 2016eb 7aSCI0040002bisacsh04a523.442231 aYeomans, Donald K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNear-Earth Objects :bFinding Them Before They Find Us /cDonald K. Yeomans.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2012] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tCHAPTER 1. Earth’s Closest Neighbors -- tCHAPTER 2. The Solar System’s Origin -- tCHAPTER 3. How and Where Do Near- Earth Objects Form? -- tCHAPTER. 4. Near- Earth Objects As the Enablers and Destroyers of Life -- tCHAPTER 5. Discovering and Tracking Near- Earth Objects -- tCHAPTER 6. The Nature of Asteroids and Comets -- tCHAPTER 7. Nature’s Natural Resources and the Human Exploration of Our Solar System -- tCHAPTER 8. Near- Earth Objects as Threats to Earth -- tCHAPTER 9. Predicting the Likelihood of an Earth Impact -- tCHAPTER 10. Deflecting an Earth- Threatening Near- Earth Object -- tReferences -- tIndex Of Asteroid And Cometary Objects -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOf all the natural disasters that could befall us, only an Earth impact by a large comet or asteroid has the potential to end civilization in a single blow. Yet these near-Earth objects also offer tantalizing clues to our solar system's origins, and someday could even serve as stepping-stones for space exploration. In this book, Donald Yeomans introduces readers to the science of near-Earth objects--its history, applications, and ongoing quest to find near-Earth objects before they find us. In its course around the sun, the Earth passes through a veritable shooting gallery of millions of nearby comets and asteroids. One such asteroid is thought to have plunged into our planet sixty-five million years ago, triggering a global catastrophe that killed off the dinosaurs. Yeomans provides an up-to-date and accessible guide for understanding the threats posed by near-Earth objects, and also explains how early collisions with them delivered the ingredients that made life on Earth possible. He shows how later impacts spurred evolution, allowing only the most adaptable species to thrive--in fact, we humans may owe our very existence to objects that struck our planet. Yeomans takes readers behind the scenes of today's efforts to find, track, and study near-Earth objects. He shows how the same comets and asteroids most likely to collide with us could also be mined for precious natural resources like water and oxygen, and used as watering holes and fueling stations for expeditions to Mars and the outermost reaches of our solar system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAsteroidsvCollisions with Earth. 0aAsteroidsxCollisions with Earth. 0aCometsvCollisions with Earth. 0aCometsxCollisions with Earth. 0aNear-Earth objects. 0aSCIENCEvAstronomy. 0aSCIENCEvSpace Science. 7aSCIENCE / Astronomy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140084463040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400844630423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400844630.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aE